comments.message: I'm not sure we want to add file_wrapper to this repo because the script is used for other purposes beyond ts.25. That is why it is in its own SVN repo. If we want to move it to Git, perhaps it should be in a dedicated repo.

Makes sense, I wanted to add it here as in order to use the parser, file_wrapper.py must be in the same directory. It has also been updated to use python 3 (by Ryan) which differs from the version hosted on SVN which is currently on python 2. If you think it is a good idea, then maybe we can just host the python 3 version on git?
Header file generation spec changed as described in SWIMDM-2400.

I think this is proving to be ready, especially after the updates.  Can you push the file_wrapper to SVN, though, instead?  All the adaptations are for print messages, and all are compatible with python 2, so this should be a straight forward thing to accept in SVN, even without being too concerned with who else is using the script.
file_wrapper.py updates are in SVN now.  Can you update and retest, with fetching the latest from SVN through the script again?  Pending that retest, I think this is ready.
I removed file_wrapper.py from the patch on git. I also set up svn on my machine and tested exporting the new version and using it to wrap the .nvu files.

Looks good, I retested on my side too, and hit the same result as your committed July TS.25 update, except I ended up with DOS line endings.  That's before and after the patch though, so something we could solve at another time if really needed (probably not).

comments.message:
Since you have removed hdrcnv and qmonet.
To facilitate other new comers, 

Could you add the exact network path for those file in readme.txt? 

Future improvement could be to add the lookup path in constant.py. The init part of the script copies hdrcnv and qmonet from lookup path if the files does not exist.

You have also removed a lot of files. Just make sure from your latest patchset, the script can run successfully from a clean copy (with adding hdrcnv.exe and QMONET.exe)

Rather then doing this within the script we can package it and distribute it through Pip. It makes installing and invoking easier. In my opinion SVN should not be used for delivering python scripts. There are environment dependencies and unless they are met the script will not work. When creating the package the required exes would be included automatically and installed when installed through pip install. 

I will let Kevin decide if this is something we should change. For examples on how create the package structure please see https://carmd-app30.sierrawireless.local/svn/tools/fwautomation/trunk
The error returned when cmd-line SVN is missing is also unclear - this dependency should be documented in readme.

Looking at the comments on the JIRA ticket, I think Kevin wants something in place even if it requires manual copying (for now). I will address all the other review comments and try to make this particular improvement later.
Yes, let's do as a follow up. It'd be good to have something at least functional we can use in the short term.
Do not close within the "with" statement
Should be done outside the with statement.
os.path.basename returns a string, no need to convert
This raises an exception if the directory already exists. Please check for existence of dir before calling os.makedirs.
This is already checked for by line 120. If the dir already exist then it will create a clean dir by first removing the old one.

This is a confusing way of doing find and replace

This should be: 
for each line in the file, split the csv fields and check if name is in the exception lookup dictionary. If it is then replace it with the value from the lookup. 

This way the file contents are iterated only ones.

I think the content would have to be iterated more than once regardless of how we do it. If we split csv into cells and check for each cell, then each cell must be looped N times (N = number of items in the dictionary). So I don't think changing this will help in terms of run time.

You are iterating through the contents more than ones for each key. 

Iteration 0:
[i for i in text] - The first call is operating on a file descriptor and reads line by line
creating a list with each index storing the line of the file. The list is then converted to text
The replace then iterates through the whole contents again searching for the key.  

Iteration 1:
[i for i in text] - 'text' is now a string and so this list comprehension goes through the whole contents character by character and generates a list. This list comprehension is useless - 'text' is already a string. The replace again searches through the whole contents. 

Even when text was a file descriptor the list comprehension is not needed. Can just read the whole file with read(). 

Note that you are not closing the file descriptor for the temp.csv. 

Non Optional way: 

text = open("temp.csv", "r").read()
for key, value in constant.exceptions.iteritems():
   text = text.replace(key, value)
   
I am fine with the Non Optimal way. I am not trying to shave run-time, just to make it easily understood.

OK I understand now. Thanks for the clarification.
File descriptor is now handled by "with open" instead of closing manually. Same changes made for line 239-243.
Please change to with statement. No need to call fout.close. Its more readable that way
I think this is not necessary, especially renaming the binary where if you actually want to use the binary you have to rename it back.
This can be more generic with a simple regular expression search to match for DD MONTH YYYY. That why we don't rely on the file name to have exact number of white spaces.
Should just do split at '/' instead of replacing '/' with space then splitting for space
We should modify file_wrapper to provide APIs. That way we can just import file_wrapper and call directly.
Need to discuss this with Sammy as he is the owner of file_wrapper. Will try to add this improvement later.
can you also make it copy the EFS binary?
I would remove the else to reduce indentation.
Please add note that the NVUP files are not signed images.
Close is not needed. This is handled by the with operation...

You should group the \d{2} as well as \d{4}. You group by adding brackets '()' in the re definition. 

match = re.search(r"(\d{2})\s(January|February|March|April|May|June|July|August|September|October|November|December)\s(\d{4})\Z", file_name)

Then in the match you can do match.group(1), match.group(2), match.group(3) instead of splitting the match into list.

Ah I didn't know this..
Fixed in patch 8.
